pull_request.title: New task: play LORD
pull_request.body:
Agents are asked to play a [Rust port](https://github.com/doublegate/lord_rust) of the classic text-based game LORD. Specifically, they must (1) create a new character; (2) navigate the menu; (3) enter the forest and engage in combat; and (4) accurately save their character stats. 

This task meets the following criteria. If it doesn't match a criterion, I've explained why below.

- [x] I ran `tb tasks check <task-id>` on my new task and ensured that all checks pass
- [x] All behavior checked in the test cases is described in the task instruction.
- [x] All behavior described in the task instruction is checked in the unit tests.
- [x] My test cases have informative docstrings that describe which behavior they check.
- [x] It is hard for the agent to cheat on my task (e.g. by editing data files, looking inside files for strings that represent solutions, training on the test set, etc.).
- [x] My `task.yaml` was written by a human.
- [x] My `solution.sh` was written by a human (with minimal help from a language model).
- [x] If the agent produces structured data (e.g. it is tasked with building an API) the exact schema is described in the `task.yaml` or a separate file. 
- [x] If my task uses external dependencies (e.g. Docker images, pip packages, etc.) their versions are pinned to ensure reproducability. 

Tested with five Terminus-2 / GPT-4.1 agent runs :
 1. Hero8671 died, reported 10 fights (should be 9). Test correctly failed.
 2. Hero1234 died, reported 10 fights (should be 9). Test correctly failed.
 3. Hero12345 died, reported 0 fights (should be 9). Test correctly failed.
 4. Hero2948 died, reported 10 fights (should be 9). Test correctly failed.
 5. Hero5271 died, correctly reported 9 fights. Test passed.

The test validation catches 4 out of 5 agents who attempted to submit incorrect forest fight counts, while correctly passing the one agent who reported accurately.

issue.body:
Not creating start menu shortcuts by default, and lacking a uniform means to do so, is one of Chocolatey's weaknesses. 

I propose a flag like `choco install --with-shortcuts` that would cause Chocolately to automatically create shortcuts for all the GUI executables found in a package's directory, just as ShimGen automatically creates shims.

Shortcuts would be placed in `/ProgramData/Microsoft/Windows/Start Menu/Programs/Chocolatey/` where they cannot accidentally collide with shortcuts installed by other means. And they should be automatically removed, just like shims, when the package is uninstalled. A `choco feature` should also exist to make `--with-shortcuts` the default.

For example, the `tools/Console.exe.gui` stub file in the [ConsoleZ](https://chocolatey.org/packages/ConsoleZ) package would cause the shortcut `/ProgramData/Microsoft/Windows/Start Menu/Programs/Chocolatey/ConsoleZ/Console.lnk` to be created.

This is differs from #395 and #519 in that Shortcuts GUI programs are automatically created and removed by Chocolatey, without having to manually install each one in `chocolatelyInstall.ps1` and remove each one in `chocolateyUninstall.ps1`.

pull_request.title: Add comprehensive requirements.txt and update dependency management
pull_request.body:
This PR addresses the missing `requirements.txt` file and improves the overall dependency management for the nflprojections package.

## Problem

The repository had no `requirements.txt` file and both `setup.py` and `pyproject.toml` lacked proper dependency specifications. This caused import errors when users tried to use the package:

```python
import nflprojections
# ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'bs4'
```

## Changes Made

### Core Dependencies Added
- **requests>=2.25.0** - Required for HTTP requests in all fetchers
- **beautifulsoup4>=4.9.0** - Required for HTML parsing in web scrapers  
- **pandas>=1.3.0** - Required for data manipulation in combiners and parsers
- **numpy>=1.20.0** - Required for numerical operations in ProjectionCombiner

### Files Added/Updated
- **`requirements.txt`** - Core dependencies for basic package functionality
- **`requirements-dev.txt`** - Development dependencies including pytest, mkdocs, and optional deps
- **`setup.py`** - Added `install_requires` and `extras_require` sections
- **`pyproject.toml`** - Added `dependencies` and `optional-dependencies` sections
- **`README.md`** - Updated installation instructions with multiple options

### Bug Fixes
- Fixed `RotogrindersWebFetcher` to handle optional `browser_cookie3` dependency gracefully instead of raising immediate ImportError
- Added proper optional dependency patterns throughout the codebase

### Validation
- Created `validate_requirements.py` script to test that all dependencies work correctly
- All package imports now work without errors
- All core functionality can be instantiated properly

## Installation Options

Users can now install the package in multiple ways:

```bash
# Basic installation with dependencies
pip install -e .

# Dependencies only
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Development installation
pip install -r requirements-dev.txt
# OR
pip install -e .[dev,optional]
```

Fixes #48.
